les of paved river channels, Southern Californians have discovered that technologically engineered solutions to flooding are just as disaster-prone as natural waterways. Jared Orsi's lively history unravels the strange and often hazardous ways that engineering, politics, and nature have come together in Los Angeles to determine the flow of water. He advances a new paradigm—the urban ecosystem—for understanding the city's complex and unpredictable waterways and other issues that are sure to play a large role in future planning. As he traces the flow of water from sky to sea, Orsi brings together many disparate and intriguing pieces of the story, including local and national politics, the little-known San Gabriel Dam fiasco, the phenomenal growth of Los Angeles, and, finally, the influence of environmentalism. Orsi provocatively widens his vision toward other cities for which Los Angeles may offer a lesson—both of things gone wrong and a glimpse of how they might be improved.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aFlood controlxGovernment policyzCaliforniazLos Angeles. 0aFlood controlzCaliforniazLos Angeles. 0aUrban ecology (Sociology)zCaliforniazLos Angeles. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh  aamerican west.  acalifornia.  acity planning.  adams.  adebris dams.  adisaster prep.  aearth sciences.  aecosystem.  aengineering.  aenvironmental history.  aenvironmentalism.  aflood control basin.  aflood control.  aflooding.  ageography.  agovernment policy.  ainfrastructure.  ala canada valley.  alos angeles river.  alos angeles.  anatural disaster.  anature.  anew years eve debris flood.  anonfiction.  apaved river channels.  apolitics.  asan gabriel dam.  ascience.  asouthern california.  astorms.  asustainability.  atechnology.  aurban ecol